    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/07-inference-serving/04-sglang-radixattention.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: The shared-prefix problem: real traffic (system prompts, few-shot blocks, agent forks, multi-turn chat) re-prefills the SAME leading tokens over and over; RadixAttention's promise is to compute each prefix's KV at most once and reuse it for any prompt that starts with it.; A radix tree is a compressed prefix trie over TOKEN IDs where each node owns the KV-cache SLOT INDICES (not tensors) for its edge \u2014 so one paged KV block can be referenced by many nodes, and the tree is a thin index layer on top of PagedAttention.; The insert path is match -> (on partial overlap) SPLIT the edge into a shared node + remainder -> attach the divergent suffix as a new leaf; no KV is recomputed on a split, only index tensors are re-sliced.; Eviction is LRU restricted to unlocked LEAVES: you peel cold tips inward so you never orphan a live prefix, lock_ref pinning protects KV a running kernel is reading, and freeing a leaf can turn its parent into a newly-evictable leaf (a cascade).\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  radix-tree\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
