    "revise": "You are the FIGURE REVISER (Opus) for \"The LLM Stack\". Chapter: content/13-interp-safety-gov/03-privacy-memorization-dp.md\nThe chapter's core intuitions: Memorization is the OPTIMAL behavior of maximum-likelihood on rare, high-surprise sequences (no generalizable rule exists, so the only way to drive loss down is to store the string in the weights) - and it is decoupled from classical overfitting because it concerns the tail of rare examples, not the average.; Three factors drive how much a string is memorized: duplication (the biggest lever, ~log n, super-linear on extractability), model scale, and context/prompt length.; The attack ladder is MIA -> extraction -> reconstruction, ordered by how much each recovers and how targeted it is.; Membership-inference success must be read as TPR at very low FPR on a log-log ROC, NOT average accuracy - a model that looks ~chance on average can still confidently leak membership for the most-vulnerable tail records, which is exactly the worst case regulators and plaintiffs surface.\n\nReview each of these figures (the ones this chapter just drew/edited):\n  privacy-memorization-scaling\n\nFor EACH: render and SEE it \u2014 `python3 scripts/preview_fig.py <NAME> --theme both` from /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook,\nthen view /tmp/figpreview/<NAME>.light.png and .dark.png. Judge strictly:\n  - Does it actually BUILD INTUITION for its concept (not just decorate)? Is it correct vs the chapter?\n  - Theme-safe (no hardcoded primary color; readable in BOTH light and dark)?\n  - Nothing clipped by the viewBox; no illegible overlaps; no tofu glyphs (ASCII only in the SVG)?\n  - Marker present in the chapter exactly once; figcaption has a bold lead + takeaway?\nIf a figure has ANY problem, FIX it: Edit /local-ssd/pk669/programming/llm-stack-textbook/figures/<NAME>.html (and re-render to confirm), or\nfix a missing/duplicate marker in the chapter. Re-verify after fixing.\n\nSet verdict per figure: good / fixed / still-broken / missing. `passed` = every figure good-or-fixed\nAND present. Return the structured object."
